# MyNet Architecture Review Rules

The current codebase is actively being redesigned and restructured.

Do not assume the existing architecture is correct.

Do not prioritize backward compatibility unless explicitly requested.

When analyzing code:
- critically evaluate existing patterns
- question current abstractions
- identify unnecessary complexity
- identify outdated designs
- identify architectural inconsistencies
- identify runtime mechanisms that should become compile-time

You are encouraged to:
- propose major redesigns
- suggest removal of obsolete systems
- simplify abstractions
- replace runtime infrastructure with generated infrastructure
- remove unnecessary layers
- reduce coupling
- improve modularity
- improve performance
- improve AOT compatibility

Prefer:
- simple architectures
- explicit designs
- compile-time safety
- deterministic behavior
- immutable infrastructure
- strongly typed APIs

Do not preserve an abstraction only because it already exists.

When appropriate:
- recommend deleting systems entirely
- recommend rebuilding systems from scratch
- recommend merging responsibilities
- recommend splitting oversized modules

Always explain:
- why the current design is problematic
- what the proposed design improves
- migration risks
- tradeoffs

The goal is long-term framework quality, not minimal changes.